Introduction
1I NTRODUCTION
This guide explains how to instal l Modular Mining’s PTX mobile plat form with N231 radio on Komatsu 
830, 930, and 980 haul trucks with Updated Operator Cab.
Note the following:
• This guide applies to PTXC7 Wi ndows CE, PTXC7 Linux, and PTX7 Linux field computers. The 
guide refers to the device s collectively as PTX. 
• PTXC7 Linux devices are PTXC7 Windows CE devi ces that have been converted to a Linux OS. 
As a result, they have the same part number as PTXC7 Windows CE device s. PTX7 devices are 
factory installed with a Linux OS.
• All PTXC cable harness part numbers also support PTX7, even thought the name specifies 
“PTXC.”
• If the mine selected the PTXC10 or PTX10 field computer for the larger display, this guide also 
applies. The only differences are that PTXC10 /PTX10 have slightly high er power consumption 
and mounting kit differences.
1.1 P RINTING  THIS GUIDE
To ensure that this guide prints as intended, disable PostScript pass-through on your printer 
before printing:
1In the PDF file, select File > Print  to display the Print window.
2Click Properties  to display the Print Properties window.
3Select Disable  from the PostScript Pass through menu:
If the guide does not print correctly with PostScript pass-throug h disabled, select File > Print > 
Advanced  > Print As Image  in the PDF file before printing.

Before You Begin
2B EFORE  YOU BEGIN
Do not install the PTX mobile pl atform unless Modular Mining’s hardware pre-configuration visit 
achieved the following:
• Personnel know where to install each hardware component. 
• Personnel know the possible routing of conduit.• All required approvals were obtained.•The Hardware Pre-Configuration Document was completed and signed by all designated mine 
personnel.
3S AFETY  WARNING  NOTICES
Warning: Always verify with the OEM/customer where to connect to power on the vehicle. And DO 
NOT ASSUME the ground location is valid. Check ground with a multimeter to avoid damaging the 
Modular Mining or OEM system.  
Warning: When choosing cable runs, to prevent tripping haz ard, do not place cables in walkways or 
standing areas. Also, do not run cables near source s of excessive heat, such as engines or air 
conditioning units, as this will damage cable integr ity leading to shorts and expose the system to 
electrical fires.  
This guide contains the follow ing Warning notice on page 14:
Warning: If a power output is enabled on a communication port, do not connect the port directly to 
an OEM device (that is not designed for it) without  first terminating that cable without power. 
Otherwise, damage to OEM systems may occur. To terminate an RJ45 Ethernet cable without 
power, refer to Proc Conn RJ-45 Large OD Wire No PWR  (PN 250038).
This guide contains the follow ing Warning notice on page 15:
Warning: Make sure you cut the blue and blue/white wires (12V DC power) when terminating the 
Ethernet cable with the RJ45 connector or you will damage the laptop or PTX unit or both .
This guide contains the follow ing Warning notices on page 55:
Warning: To help prevent multipath errors and signal loss, any metallic structure (masts, panels, 
boxes, etc.) within two feet of any GPS antenna should never be above the antenna's ground plane 
height. As a general rule, the antenna's view of the sk y to the horizon should be as free from metallic 
obstructions as possible .
Warning: Do not supply power to the N231 radio unless the radio is connected to an antenna, or you 
may damage the radio.

General Welding Guidelines
4G ENERAL  WELDING  GUIDELINES
The following welding guidelines are for mine sta ff or mine contractors. Modular Mining employees 
shall not perform any welding activities.
Welding Guidelines
Always refer to and follow the equipment ma nufacturer’s standard welding guidelines.
Follow all mine-specifi c requirements and proc edures for welding.
If specific equipment manufacture r’s welding standards are not avai lable, welders should follow a 
local industry standard welding guideline, such as, but not limited to:
•AWS (American Welding Society) .
•ISO (International St andards Organization) .
•CSA (Canadian Standards Association) .
• AS/NZS (Australian/New Zealand Standards).
Before welding, ensure that the main power of  the equipment is completely de-energized and 
locked out for safety.
Protect all MMS components with welding protecti on materials. Welding protection materials may 
include welding blankets, welding curtains, and welding screens. The welding protection materials 
must be high heat resistant, no n-flammable, non-melting, and sp ark-resistant. You must use the 
materials to isolate, cover, and protect all Modular Mining hardware components (hardware, enclosures, conduit, coax cabl es, power cables/wires, wiring harnesses, antennas, etc.) from:
•S p a r k s .
• Welding slag.• Molten metal.• Extreme high heat.• Arc from heavy welding.• The torch flame.
Do not connect welding ground leads directly to any Modular Mining hardware, enclosures, 
masts, etc.
Do not lay welding cables over or  near the equipment electrical harnesses. Doing so might induce 
welding voltage into the electrical harn ess and cause damage to components.
Fully cover all finished welds with rust-inhibiting paint. The paint color should match the color of 
the surrounding base surface and should be appr oved by the controlling maintenance department 
for each equipment type.
Modular Mining recommends inspecting all welds as part of standard system checks. Repair or 
repaint cracks or other visi ble defects, as necessary.

Differences Between PTXC7 and PTX7
6D IFFERENCES  BETWEEN  PTXC7 AND PTX7
•PCAP Glass Touchscreen
•Slightly Higher Power Input Consumption
•Increased Power Output Capability
•Power On Set to “IGN Only” by Default
•CAN Termination - Built In
•PTX IP Addresses
6.1 PCAP G LASS TOUCHSCREEN  
PTX7 includes a Projected Capacitance (PCAP) to uch screen, which has a top layer of 1.8 mm 
chemically strengthened glass. As such, it is highly scratch resist ant, so no protective overlay is 
required. However, customers may use an overlay if de sired. The touch screen is sensitive enough that 
operators may wear gloves when using the screen.
Cleaning the touch screen is similar to cleaning a cell phone. You can use a soft lint-free cloth or 
microfiber cloth. You can also use a small amount of plain water, mild soap, or ammonia-free glass 
cleaner. Apply the cleaning solution  to the cloth, then use the clot h to clean the screen. Do not use 
abrasive cleaning products that will scratch the screen.
6.2 S LIGHTLY  HIGHER  POWER  INPUT  CONSUMPTION
PTX7 requires slightly more power input at 12.5W (12V input) or 15.0W (24V input) than PTXC7 did 
at 9.2W (both input voltages). This increases by  7.2W if setting the PTX7 to the maximum display 
brightness, which results in a total of 19.7W (12V in put) or 22.2W (24V input). This does not include 
any additional power consumption resulting from the use of the "clean12V" or "Power Pass-Through" 
(PPT) power output ports.
6.3 I NCREASED  POWER  OUTPUT  CAPABILITY  
PTX7 is capable of 1A of output power on both power output ports. This clean12V is more than the 
PTXC7 series, which provided 770mA. The PPT current is similar and is 1A.
The power 
output on the Ethernet 1 and Ethernet 2 ports is known as passive PoE because it does not 
adhere to the 48V standard but just provides a DC power output.
• Clean12V output (shared between the DC Jack, CO M 3, and Ethernet1). This is enabled/on by
default. This 12V output is from the prim ary internal DC/DC regulated power supply.Note: The max backlight intensity of the PTX7 is much higher than the PTXC7 at around 900 NITs 
(default is 350 NITs) as compared to 300 Nits. Daylight readability is easily achieved without setting 
to the max brightness.

Differences Between PTXC7 and PTX7
• PPT output (shared between CAN 1, CAN 2, and Ethernet 2). This is di sabled/off by default. 
The output voltage tracks the input voltage closel y since it is "passed-through" from the input.
To change the state of the PTX power output po rts, you connect to the PTX and run commands that 
are specific to the PTX type. Fo r PTX7, for example, running the sudo ptxapp -y on  command 
enables PPT. This is necessary if  you need to power CAN device s on the PTXC Cable harness. 
Below are the commands for turning on/off clean12V and PPT on PTX7:
• Clean12V on/off:
•sudo ptxapp -x on 
•sudo ptxapp -x off 
• PPT on/off
•sudo ptxapp -y on  
•sudo ptxapp -y off
Important: Always be careful when connecting the Ethernet ports to external devices as some 
products may be damaged by the presence of "passive PoE" on the unused twisted pairs .
For instructions about enabling PPT for PTXC7  Windows CE, PTXC7 Linux, and PTX7, see Changing 
Power Output Settings on the PTX, If Necessary .
6.4 P OWER  ON SET TO “IGN O NLY” BY DEFAULT
For more information, see Only if Required: Enable Keep-Alive Mode (PTX7 Only) .
6.5 CAN T ERMINATION  - B UILT IN 
Unlike PTXC7, PTX7 contains an internal CAN terminat or in each of its two independent CAN ports. 
The CAN terminators are software co nfigurable and enabled by default. Therefore, take care to avoid 
having redundant terminators at the PTX7. For instructions, see Remove CAN Terminators from 
PTXC Cable Harness (PTX7 Only) .

Changing Power Output Settings on the PTX, If Necessary
9C HANGING  POWER  OUTPUT  SETTINGS  ON THE PTX, I F NECESSARY
Clean12V power output on the PTX is shared between the DC Jack,  COM3, and Ethernet 1 and is 
enabled/on by default.
Power Pass-Through (PPT) on the PTX is shared between CAN 1, CAN 2, and Ethernet 2 and is 
disabled/off by default. So, if you need to power CAN devices connected to th e PTXC cable harness, you 
must enable PPT on the PTX. 
Note: On PTXC Windows CE devices, the PPT power output is called PoE in the firmware .
Note: Currently, the only MTS CAN devices  that will be connected to the PTXC cable harness 
are Guided Spotting 
DVI display devices. 
Warning: If a power output is enabled on a communication port, do not connect the port directly to 
an OEM device (that is not designed for it) without  first terminating that cable without power. 
Otherwise, damage to OEM systems may occur. To terminate an RJ45 Ethernet cable without 
power, refer to Proc Conn RJ-45 Large OD Wire No PWR  (PN 250038).
The tasks are:
•Modify Ethernet Cable 106112
•Physically Connect to the PTX Unit
•Configure the Laptop IP Address to be on the Same Subnet as the PTX Ethernet 1 IP Address
•Enable/Disable Clean12V and/or PPT/PoE on the PTX
•Disconnect the Components

Required parts: Ethernet cable 1 06112 and an RJ45 connector (107766). 
1Cut the RJ45 connector off the end of Ethernet cable 106112.
2Terminate the cable with a new R J45 connector (107766). Terminate it without  the blue and 
white/blue wires. Follow the instructions in crimping guide Proc Conn RJ-45 Large OD Wire No 
PWR  (PN 250038).

9.2 P HYSICALLY  CONNECT  TO THE PTX U NIT
On the test bench,  do the following: 
1Connect the PTXC cable harness to the PTX unit.
2Connect the harness Power In cable to  the 12 or 24 VDC power supply.
3Connect the modified Ethernet cable (106112) between the PTX and the laptop. 
aScrew the M12 connector on the modified Ethernet cable into the back of the PTX.
bAttach the “new” RJ45 connector on the modified Ethernet cable to an Ethernet port on the laptop. 
4Turn on power to the PTX.
9.3 C ONFIGURE  THE LAPTOP  IP A DDRESS  TO BE ON THE SAME SUBNET  AS THE PTX 
ETHERNET  1 IP A DDRESS
To complete this procedure, you need to know the PTX unit’s Ethern et 1 IP address and subnet mask. 
The default primary Ethernet 1 IP address and subnet mask for PTXC7 Windows CE, PTXC7 Linux, 
and PTX7 are the same: 192.168.0.111 and 255.255.255.0, respectively. 
Note: If the PTX was used previously in the field, you need to obtain the PTX IP address from 
the mine.
1On the laptop, open the Control Panel.
2In the Control Panel, click Network and Sharing Center .
3In the window that appears, click Change adapter settings . 
4Right-click the laptop’s Ethernet connection ic on, such as Local Area Connection, and select 
Properties  from the menu. 
5Double-click Internet Protocol Version 4 (TCP/IPv4) . 
6Select Use the following IP address :
